[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'warnings. Click the logo in the top left corner, open extensions, go to missing nodes, and install everything that\'s required. One thing worth mentioning, sometimes the Bernini R node gets installed as an older version'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automatically. If that happens, you may still see missing node errors even after updating. To fix this, go back to extensions, find Bernini R, open version, switch to the latest release or the nightly build, and update again. For'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the models, simply follow the node I provided and place them in the corresponding folders. Before we dive into the workflow itself, let\'s briefly talk about what Bernini R actually does. Bernini R feels different'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from traditional video generation. Instead of generating from scratch, it focuses more on understanding and editing existing video. That means editing content, maintaining consistency, handling longer sequences,'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and running locally. Let\'s jump into the workflows. We just took a quick look at some of Bernini R\'s workflow examples, and there are actually this many. Honestly, when I opened it for the first time, I was a'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little confused, too. I 2 I, T 2 V, V 2 V, and even RV 2 V. It almost feels like suddenly entering some kind of abbreviation hell. But once you understand Bernini R\'s design'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'philosophy, you realize the categorization is actually very intuitive. Basically, everything is organized around what is the input and how does it become a video? First is I 2 I, image to image. You input an image and modify or reconstruct'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the content. Next is T 2 V, text to video. Generate a video directly from text. Then comes V 2 V, video to video. Input an existing video, then edit or transform it. And finally, RV 2 V,'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference video to video. This is where things start getting interesting. Besides the video itself, it also uses additional reference information to control the output, making characters, motion, or style more stable. Once you'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understand these four categories, the remaining workflows suddenly become a lot less intimidating. At this point, some people may wonder, "Didn\'t we just say Bernini R is more focused on video editing? Then why does it still have I 2 I and T 2 V?"'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Actually, video editing doesn\'t always have to start from video. A lot of the time, people first use images to establish characters, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; generate assets quickly with text, and then move into video editing afterward.'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, the key idea of Bernini R isn\'t the input format. It\'s that different types of input all eventually connect into the same controllable video pipeline. Once you understand this, the rest of the workflows become much easier to'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'follow. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; But here, I\'m not going to break down every workflow one by one. Because although there seem to be many of them, the structure is actually very consistent. You can think of it as continuously'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'adding more input sources onto the same underlying skeleton. The most basic one is T2V. No source input at all. It creates an empty latent and lets the model generate starting from text. If you\'re familiar with video workflows,'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll notice this is actually very close to a standard 1.2.1 video generation pipeline. Next are I2I and V2V. Their overall structures are actually very similar.'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The only difference is the source material. I2I takes images. V2V takes videos. The source is first encoded, then injected into the generation pipeline for editing.'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And finally, RV2V. On top of the video, it adds an additional reference image. This creates two source streams controlling the result at the same time. So structurally, [music] it\'s basically blank generation, add image, add video,'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'add reference control. The core generation process barely changes. You\'re simply injecting more context into the system. Once you understand the structure, the later nodes and parameters become'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much easier to understand. Next, let\'s look at how to use these workflow nodes and where people most commonly run into problems. Using RV2V as an example, first, [music] choose an image as the reference image,'

[05:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then choose a video as the target video. The goal is to modify the target video using the reference image. And here is where you enter the editing prompt. You can also adjust the output video resolution here. Make sure the'

[05:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference image uses the same resolution as well. Otherwise, it will end up looking like this. Okay. Now, let\'s move on to the two most important nodes inside Bernini R. Source stream and guider.'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Of course, the other nodes matter, too, but the ones you\'ll actually spend time tuning are mostly these two. Well, I guess that was kind of obvious. &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Let\'s start with source stream. There\'s'

[06:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an important parameter called source ID. Its job is actually very simple. It tells the model where this piece of information comes from. For example, in R V2V, source ID equals one is usually the source video. Source'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ID equals two is usually the reference image. The model uses different source streams to understand which parts should preserve original motion and which parts should follow the new character or style.'

[06:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, if you see two source streams in a workflow, don\'t assume it\'s complicated. At its core, [music] you\'re simply giving the model an extra source of context. Now, let\'s look at guider. At first glance, it can feel overwhelming because'

[06:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there are a lot of parameters. But in practice, most of them rarely need adjustment. First, just set mode to auto. It automatically selects the proper mode based on the number of connected streams. One parameter worth paying'

[06:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'attention to is APG. In plain language, it controls how much freedom the model has. The stronger it is, the more the model preserves original content. Creativity decreases, but stability increases.'

[07:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then we have the three most important parameters, omega V, omega I, and omega TI. Omega V controls how much original video content is preserved. If motion drifts or scenes deform,'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'increase this. Omega I controls reference image influence. If characters don\'t resemble the reference image or outfit consistency is weak, increase this. Omega TI controls text prompt strength.'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If prompts barely have any effect, raise this value. It\'s actually easy to remember. V equals video, I equals image, TI equals text. As for Ada, momentum, and norm'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'threshold, leave them alone for now. The defaults are usually stable enough. The later omega scale and boundary settings mainly matter for the 14B model. For 1 3B, you can mostly ignore them.'

[08:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Once you understand these parameters, you\'ve basically understood Bernini R\'s core tuning logic. Enough theory. Now it\'s time for the most enjoyable part, testing. Actually, while explaining the parameters earlier,'

