AUDIO: 'are quite strong and completely match the description. But honestly, [music] a lot of models can already do T2V and I2I. That\'s not the part I care about most. What\'s really interesting is video editing'

[09:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'capability. So next, we\'ll focus on V2V and RV2V. This is where we find out if it\'s actually a local omni system or just another video pipeline. First, V2V. Input an existing video, for example,'

[09:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] a person walking in a park. Then use prompts to change the scene into winter, add snowfall, while preserving character motion and camera movement as much as possible. What we\'re testing here is, is it'

[09:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually editing or simply regenerating? It perfectly captures the character while successfully preserving both the original motion and the camera movement, all wrapped up in a beautiful snowy atmosphere.'

[10:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Finally, our V2V. This is also the workflow I find the most valuable. This time, besides the original video, we also add a reference image. For example, preserve the motion and camera movement from the original video,'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but replace the character clothing style using the reference image. Or directly replace the entire character appearance. This test makes it easiest to see whether Source Stream is truly working and whether Bernina can achieve'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'controllable video editing. Wow, that actually surprised me. It replaced the person directly, but the mouth movements during speech were lost. I tried it a few times, and it seems that as long as the character in the'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video isn\'t speaking, the results can work quite well. At the same time, I also found that it performs really well when changing the background.'

[10:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Although it may seem capable of running on less than 3 GB of VRAM, in practice, it\'s not suitable for editing very long videos. Otherwise, you can easily run into OOM errors. Another issue is that the processing'

[11:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'speed is really slow. Unless there\'s an existing video you really like and only want to fix a few small imperfections, in most cases, I\'d still recommend regenerating the video from scratch'

[11:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because the overall time investment can end up being higher. Or, before committing to a full edit, try processing a short clip first to check the results, then decide whether you want to adjust the parameters and continue. Finally, let\'s talk about the'

[11:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
